hies, petitions, and government papers, Kelderman offers an interdisciplinary method for examining how Native authors claimed a place in public discourse, and how the conventions of Indian diplomacy shaped their texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aIndian Removal, 1813-1903. 0aIndians of North AmericaxGovernment relationsy1789-1869. 0aIndians of North AmericazUnited StatesxHistoriography. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aHistory : American History. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Nineteenth-Century Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847619340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438476193423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438476193/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles